apanese female figures who have refused to sit quietly on the sidelines of history. The contributors move beyond archival portraits to consider historically and culturally informed diva imagery and diva lore. The diva is ripe for expansion, fantasy, eroticization, and playful reinvention, while simultaneously presenting a challenge to patriarchal culture. Diva Nation asks how the diva disrupts or bolsters ideas about nationhood, morality, and aesthetics.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2023) 0aWomen in popular culturezJapan. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / General.2bisacsh  aaesthetics.  aancient goddesses.  aarchival portraits.  acensure.  adebate.  adiva imagery.  adiva lore.  aemulation.  aeroticization.  afamous women.  afantasy.  afemale icon.  afemale iconicity.  ahistoric.  ajapan.  ajapanese female figures.  ajapanese.  amodern singers.  amodern writers.  amorality.  anationhood.  apatriarchal culture.  aplayful reinvention.  aqueens.  asidelines of history.  astrong women.1 aBardsley, Jan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCopeland, Rebecca, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCopeland, Rebecca, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHartley, Barbara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHein, Laura, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHolloway, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMiller, Laura, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMiller, Laura, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMonden, Masafumi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRokudenashiko,, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc